      "@charl In 1.4 there will be a new way of passing values to JS code. Essentially, if your `r.js` code evaluates to a function you'll be able to invoke the function with arguments to pass in RQL values.\r\n\r\nHere's your above test expressed using the new syntax:\r\n\r\n```ruby\r\n> r([1,2,3]).map{r.js(\"function(val) { return val}\")}.run\r\n[1,2,3]\r\n```\r\n\r\nI hope you agree that this is much clearer than trying to bind `this`."
